I need you to get me a
meeting with Aidan Coulter.

135
00:06:16,710 --> 00:06:17,939
- Oh, Aidan Coulter?
- Yes.

136
00:06:18,011 --> 00:06:21,641
Uh... What? I sat next to
him once at an A's game.

137
00:06:21,715 --> 00:06:22,910
And the story I remember

138
00:06:22,983 --> 00:06:25,452
is that you two were talking
smack that entire game.

139
00:06:25,518 --> 00:06:27,282
And after he spilled
his beer on you

140
00:06:27,354 --> 00:06:30,222
and insisted on buying you a
new jacket, you refused him.

141
00:06:30,590 --> 00:06:31,717
So he owes you.

142
00:06:32,225 --> 00:06:34,545
Just get me a meeting. I will
handle everything from there.

143
00:06:36,062 --> 00:06:38,531
Okay. I'll see what I can do.

144
00:06:38,732 --> 00:06:40,360
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

145
00:06:49,276 --> 00:06:50,505
Huh.

146
00:06:52,178 --> 00:06:54,738
You'll be fine. You've
had liver biopsies before.

147
00:06:54,948 --> 00:06:56,576
And they've always hurt a lot.

148
00:06:57,851 --> 00:06:59,376
Please, is there another way?

149
00:06:59,452 --> 00:07:01,764
Well, the other way, Eric,
would be going through your neck,

150
00:07:01,788 --> 00:07:03,468
and I don't think you'd
like that any more.

151
00:07:03,757 --> 00:07:06,921
Eric, you know why NBA players
all wear headphones before games?

152
00:07:07,460 --> 00:07:09,820
Now, don't look at him. Look
at me. I need you to answer me.

153
00:07:10,297 --> 00:07:12,562
Why do NBA players wear
headphones before games?

154
00:07:13,199 --> 00:07:15,964
I don't know. I
guess they like music.

155
00:07:16,136 --> 00:07:17,729
No, they need music.

156
00:07:17,804 --> 00:07:20,069
Music helps them forget
about everything else

157
00:07:20,140 --> 00:07:21,665
and focus on what's important.

158
00:07:21,741 --> 00:07:23,073
The game.

159
00:07:23,977 --> 00:07:25,104
Who's your favorite player?

160
00:07:25,478 --> 00:07:26,673
Curry.

161
00:07:26,746 --> 00:07:30,877
Okay. This is the song he
listens to before every game.

162
00:07:31,918 --> 00:07:32,977
How do you know?

163
00:07:33,053 --> 00:07:34,885
Because he's my
favorite player, too.

164
00:07:35,655 --> 00:07:39,217
I want you to close your
eyes and focus on this.

165
00:07:39,659 --> 00:07:40,922
Just this.

166
00:07:43,797 --> 00:07:45,197
- It's cold.
- Yeah, now it is.

167
00:07:45,265 --> 00:07:47,860
But if you stay focused,
pretty soon it'll stop feeling cold

168
00:07:47,934 --> 00:07:49,061
and start to feel warm.

169
00:07:49,269 --> 00:07:50,813
When that happens, I
want you to nod your head,

170
00:07:50,837 --> 00:07:53,830
and you'll feel some
pressure and a small pinch.

171
00:07:54,641 --> 00:07:56,906
- But what if it doesn't?
- Now close your eyes

172
00:07:56,977 --> 00:07:58,240
and focus.

173
00:08:03,783 --> 00:08:04,842
You ready?

174
00:08:18,198 --> 00:08:19,826
Two minutes,
he'll be good to go.

175
00:08:20,667 --> 00:08:22,227
How'd you know he
was a basketball fan?

176
00:08:23,103 --> 00:08:24,162
His shoes.

177
00:08:24,971 --> 00:08:26,051
He's not wearing any shoes.

178
00:08:26,373 --> 00:08:27,973
Yeah, they're in a
backpack in his room.

179
00:08:29,009 --> 00:08:30,272
You searched his backpack?

180
00:08:31,111 --> 00:08:34,445
Well, it's less
invasive than a rectal

181
00:08:34,514 --> 00:08:36,176
and, most of the
time, more useful.

182
00:08:39,786 --> 00:08:41,448
Okay, Spirit, just
keep still and...

183
00:08:41,521 --> 00:08:45,219
"And during a few parts of the exam,
we may ask you to hold your breath,

184
00:08:45,291 --> 00:08:46,884
"but it'll only be
a few seconds."

185
00:08:47,060 --> 00:08:48,392
You got it.

186
00:08:51,631 --> 00:08:53,395
You gonna buy a tux or rent one?

187
00:08:55,068 --> 00:08:56,400
The fundraiser is black-tie.

188
00:08:57,003 --> 00:08:59,768
I have a suit. It's new.

189
00:08:59,839 --> 00:09:02,138
I bought it for my
resident interviews.

190
00:09:02,475 --> 00:09:05,309
It doesn't matter how
new it is. It's not a tux.

191
00:09:06,713 --> 00:09:09,979
Wearing a uniform at
work reassures patients.

192
00:09:10,050 --> 00:09:11,450
Wearing a uniform at a party

193
00:09:11,518 --> 00:09:14,181
does nothing but make
you hot and uncomfortable.

194
00:09:14,687 --> 00:09:15,848
This party is work.

195
00:09:16,356 --> 00:09:19,520
Get a tux. And not a crappy
one from some outlet store.

196
00:09:19,659 --> 00:09:22,026
Get fitted by a pro and
spend a minimum of two grand.

197
00:09:22,262 --> 00:09:24,006
You're gonna meet rich
people who can help your career.

198
00:09:24,030 --> 00:09:25,641
And they're not gonna wanna
help some slob in a suit...

199
00:09:25,665 --> 00:09:26,689
I'm not a slob.

200
00:09:27,700 --> 00:09:31,432
No, I am very clean and make
sure my clothes are never wrinkled.

201
00:09:31,504 --> 00:09:33,063
And it's too big.

202
00:09:35,075 --> 00:09:40,104
Her heart, it's enlarged
53% since her last exam.

203
00:09:41,614 --> 00:09:43,412
Her last exam was
only six months ago.

204
00:09:43,583 --> 00:09:44,915
It won't fit.

205
00:09:46,119 --> 00:09:47,178
Too big.

206
00:09:47,587 --> 00:09:49,783
The biopsy confirmed
acute cellular rejection.

207
00:09:49,856 --> 00:09:51,552
We maximized his
immunosuppressives, but...

208
00:09:51,624 --> 00:09:52,683
I found one.

209
00:09:52,926 --> 00:09:54,189
A type-O liver.

210
00:09:54,360 --> 00:09:55,453
Are you sure?

211
00:09:55,628 --> 00:09:57,706
Park and I checked the
registry, and there weren't any.

212
00:09:57,730 --> 00:09:59,028
I found it online.

213
00:09:59,099 --> 00:10:01,967
He, uh, already tried to make a
direct donation a few months ago,

214
00:10:02,035 --> 00:10:03,765
but the patient died
before the surgery.

215
00:10:04,404 --> 00:10:06,430
I contacted him,
which wasn't easy,

216
00:10:07,040 --> 00:10:08,599
but he still wants
to be a donor.

217
00:10:09,542 --> 00:10:11,408
That's amazing. Great job.

218
00:10:12,278 --> 00:10:13,507
What's the catch?

219
00:10:13,580 --> 00:10:15,558
He wants to be a donor,
but he's not on the registry.

220
00:10:15,582 --> 00:10:16,982
I mean, there's
got to be a catch.

221
00:10:18,084 --> 00:10:20,576
He, uh... Well, he
can't be on the registry

222
00:10:20,954 --> 00:10:22,616
because he is in prison.

223
00:10:23,823 --> 00:10:24,916
For murder.

224
00:10:25,425 --> 00:10:28,259
Actually, um, seven murders.

225
00:10:34,234 --> 00:10:38,330
Boris Tirayan was a Russian mafia
enforcer convicted of seven murders.

226
00:10:38,505 --> 00:10:40,133
Who now wants to make amends.

227
00:10:40,306 --> 00:10:41,934
He tried to be a donor
a few months ago,

228
00:10:42,008 --> 00:10:44,568
but the patient died before the
red tape could be worked out.

229
00:10:44,911 --> 00:10:46,243
But now it has.

230
00:10:46,579 --> 00:10:49,105
Are there any laws against
an inmate becoming a donor?

231
00:10:49,516 --> 00:10:53,009
No. But there is a ton of liability.
What if he attacks someone here?

232
00:10:53,186 --> 00:10:55,546
He'll be guarded by state
prison guards on a separate level,

233
00:10:55,588 --> 00:10:57,523
away from patients and
all non-essential staff.

234
00:10:57,757 --> 00:10:59,837
Everyone deserves a
chance to turn their life around.

235
00:10:59,926 --> 00:11:02,725
Guy wants to do something
decent, we should let him.

236
00:11:02,795 --> 00:11:04,957
I don't think we owe
a murderer anything.

237
00:11:05,031 --> 00:11:07,967
But maybe he owes us
something. He has a debt to society.

238
00:11:08,201 --> 00:11:11,603
Which he would repay by
donating his inner organs?

239
00:11:11,671 --> 00:11:14,539
Isn't it a slippery slope between
a guy who wants to make amends

240
00:11:14,607 --> 00:11:17,771
and turning our prison system
into a superstore for body parts?

241
00:11:17,844 --> 00:11:20,109
A slippery slope that
saves a child's life.

242
00:11:20,980 --> 00:11:22,140
<i>It'll never happen.</i>

243
00:11:22,182 --> 00:11:24,693
He's just trying to get to a hospital
where it'll be easier to escape.

244
00:11:24,717 --> 00:11:26,379
You have no idea
